properties.Title: Starting Election Regulations
properties.UserDescription:
Elections may only be started on day 1, 8, 15, 22 and 29. In case an office is vacant, citizens may start an election immediately. The term of that official will end on the next regular election day.
This means, in code, that elections may only be started if the world age in days modulo 7 is less than 1. Example: on the middle of world day 15, the world is 14.5 days old. 14.5 mod 7 is 0.5 and therefore less than 1.

civics.name: [C] Unica Salary Legislation
civics.description:
Every hour, every the Governing Mayor for Unica gets a wage according to the index wage. The index wage is automatically adjusted based on inflation. Wages are paid out of the unica wages account so the Governor has to make sure to keep this account stocked up. Owed wages are tracked.
The governor also receive a pension that is based on the index wage as well. The longer they serve, the more pension they receive. Pension payments are capped at 70% of the index wage.

properties.UserDescription: Wages that are not paid out are remembered and citizens can check how much wages the governor owes them with the !unicawagesowed chat command.

properties.Title: Declaration of Protest
properties.UserDescription: If a citizen enters the message !protest, they declare that they want to hold a protest. A message that a protest is started is sent to the government of unica and the citizen gets the right to place certain objects on the capital roads for the next 60 minutes.

properties.Title: Right to Protest
properties.UserDescription: Citizens have the right to peacefully protest. They may do so by gathering on a public property like the capital roads. This includes using vehicles, signs, chairs, benches or construction posts to sit on or block off property. They will have to bring pre-written signs because Eco does not allow to track the "write text on sign" action so we can override the permission for it. A protest is only valid as long as at least one citizen is physically present. Courts may order a protest to dissolve if the interest of the public on dissolving it is higher than the interest of the protesting individuals to exercise their basic rights. The latter is considered high as long as the impact of the protest is avoidable. If the senate is in session and at least three members of the senate are physically present in the senate, protests may not take place in a radius of five claims around the senate building. Likewise, if a court is in session at the court house, no protest may take place in a radius of five claims around it.
